questiontext.text:
Exercise

Using the triangle \(ABC\) which can be regarded as one half of the equilateral triangle \(ABD\), calculate sin, cos, tan for the angles \(30^\circ\) and \(60^\circ\).

Give exact answers.

\(\sin 30^\circ =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]

\(\cos 30^\circ =\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]

\(\tan 30^\circ =\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]

\(\sin 60^\circ =\) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]

\(\cos 60^\circ =\) [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] [[feedback:prt5]]

\(\tan 60^\circ =\) [[input:ans6]] [[validation:ans6]] [[feedback:prt6]]

generalfeedback.text:
By Pythagoras' theorem: \[(BC)^2=(AB)^2-(AC)^2=x^2-\dfrac{x^2}{4}=\dfrac{3x^2}{4} \quad\text{so} \quad BC=x\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\]

Hence:

\[\sin30^\circ=\dfrac{AC}{AB} = \dfrac{\frac{x}{2}}{x} = {@ta1@}, \qquad \cos30^\circ=\dfrac{BC}{AB} = \dfrac{x\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}{x} = {@ta2@}\]

\[ \tan 30^\circ = \dfrac{\frac{1}{2}}{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}} = {@ta3@}\]

and

\[\sin60^\circ=\dfrac{BC}{AB} = \dfrac{x\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}{x}= {@ta4@}, \qquad \cos60^\circ=\dfrac{AC}{AB} = {@ta5@}\]

\[\tan60^\circ = \dfrac{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}{\frac{1}{2}} = {@ta6@}\]
